## Pros of this approach vs your current procedural approver

| Aspect | Current procedural approver | This ReAct approver |
|---|---|---|
| Reliability | 100% deterministic | Depends on LLM |
| Flexibility | Only "approve N" / "reject N" / "list" | Any natural language |
| Response quality | Template string | LLM-written, contextual |
| SCM intelligence | None (just DB data) | Urgency alerts, remark interpretation |
| Token cost | Zero | ~3,000-5,000 per request |
| Latency | ~100ms | ~2-5 seconds |
| Failure modes | DB errors only | LLM parse errors, timeouts |

For the APPROVER persona specifically, this ReAct approach makes more sense than for creator/reviewer. Here's why: the approver is a MANAGER reading a SUMMARY and making a DECISION. The LLM's ability to interpret `AI_VERIFICATION_REMARK`, flag urgency, and present information clearly adds real value. The action (approve/reject) is a single integer — low risk of LLM format failure.

For CREATOR (which needs `resource_id`, `project_id`, `task_idx`, `activity_idx`, `start_date`, `end_date`, `plan_hrs` all in structured JSON), the ReAct pattern is still risky unless using a model with native tool calling.

